<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the College of Life Sciences at the University of Dundee (WSC036)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the College of Life Sciences at the University of Dundee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (WSC036)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This evidence is submitted on behalf of the College of Life Sciences at the University of Dundee.  In response to the questions posed by the Commons Select committee about women in STEM careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">academic staff in the College of Life Sciences at the University of Dundee collected and summarised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">comments/ideas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">professors, postdocs and students.  There are no connections to lobbying groups or financial interests to declare in this context.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A common theme reported by young women researchers is that they experience multiple everyday assumptions (about them) and inequalities that have the cumulative effect of m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aking them feel that they didn't/don’t 'fit'. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">People can be more-or-less vulnerable to these effects, depending on their age, experience, and what else is happening in their lives. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Science is perceived as a risky career with limited job security. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Wome</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n appear to be more risk averse. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Some women report that the financial reward is not sufficient for the commitment required.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The cultural attitudes in Science are often cited as a problem. This includes for example, the aggressively competitive nature of t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he business and the constant competition for funding and or publication of data in high impact journals.  Success in academia requires long hours of work in the laboratory, international recognition of research requires academics to travel to international</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> meetings. These demands are not always compatible with a good work life balance and this is more of a concern to women.    </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Collegiality is not supported or encouraged by any of the current academic assessment criteria e.g. REF. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This may relate to the cur</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rent system of how research output and thus someone’s value is measured.  </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women do not want to be seen as (too) competitive or aggressive. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The difficulty of raising a family while building this career is often reported as appearing insurmountable.  Howe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ver, childcare issues can be solved by ‘throwing money’ at the situation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Anecdotally, the types of choices we see are teaching, media/communication industry, charity work, childcare.  It </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is noticeable that most editors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of science journals are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">female as are the majority of staff in funding councils and charities like CR-UK, AICR,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Wellcome Trust, etc.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in differ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">ent employment sectors?</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We are losing highly trained people whose skills are lost to the scientific community.  This loss of diversity in creativity, thinking patterns, specialty talent, etc. maybe detrimental to our ability to generate the best solutions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to the world’s problems.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There may be a benefit to having scientifically trained people move into other sectors – this could improve rigour of thought and practice and improve evidence-based decision-making and general scientific literacy of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">population.  However, a move into other sectors should be the choice of an individual, and not be perceived</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> as a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">necessity.  If mostly women make such alternate choice, these other sectors will also start to suffer from lack of diversity. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should uni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">versities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">?</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More overt mentoring and support for women academics at all career level needs to be provided.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities should provide more targeted career advice to undergraduate students that emphasizes the career opportunities for women in academia.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities should prioritize funding schemes to support women at key stages of their career. For many academ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ics a critical point comes at child-bearing ages – postdoc level.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A number of options can help here: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A funding scheme for working in small focused teams (a post-doctoral and a technician) to deliver a research project where both could be part-time and t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ogether continue to be research productive at a high level.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Flexible working for parental responsibilities for men as well as women.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Establishing clear career progression pathways that accommodate time-out for children.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities need to ensure that lea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ders and managers fully understand equality and diversity as it relates to gender issues.  For example University could have mandatory training programs.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities need to ensure that there is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">transparency and clarity about what is expected at all caree</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r levels. Clarity about why decisions were made, is important. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It makes a huge difference when decisions are accompanied by explanations, particularly when the decisions have unpleasant consequences. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are many good examples of good practise that ar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e evaluated and collated by the Athena SWAN scheme.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government should provide ring fenced funding to support University initiatives aimed at facilitating the careers of women academics.  For example, hiring technicians to support the research activities of female academics on maternity leave. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The gover</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nment should invest in social science research to identify why females in STEM subjects make career choices to leave academia.  This will inform about appropriate interventions.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government should consider education in a minimum of two science subjects </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">compulsory for all pupils until age 16.  This would increase the pool of women entering into STEM subjects.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>